{"actual_usd":0.15948500000000002,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":245,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31162,"reply":"\"Yeah—if he were only a teacher with unusually good bedside manner, the cross would be weirdly excessive.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square where the well chain gives a little metal tick.* \"A great life can show you what love looks like. It can't do much about guilt.\"\n\n\"If the problem is just ignorance, then sure—send a wise man. If the problem is sin, rebellion, death, estrangement from God... then example alone doesn't reach far enough. I can be shown the good and still fail to do it. Worse, I can know the good and be guilty anyway.\"\n\n\"The Christian claim is that Jesus doesn't only model love—he bears something. He takes judgment, reconciles, atones, does the thing I cannot do by admiring him harder. Otherwise the cross turns into a tragic visual aid, which is... honestly pretty grim.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench a second, thinking.* \"A moral example can inspire you. A Savior has to save you. That difference is the whole thing, really.\"\n\n\"What part are you pressing on most—the justice of it, or whether atonement itself makes sense?\"","rolling_24h_usd":45.080810000000035,"run_id":"bdc05760-8180-4577-b090-6db35a08d27d"}
